Olim *Prometheus*, Iapetī fīlius prīmus, hominēs ex lutō **fingēbat**. Simul *Vulcānus* ex lutō fēminam **faciēbat**. *Minerva* huic fēminae animam **dedit** et omnēs deī dōna eī **misērunt**. ob id nōmen “*Pandōra*” ei **datum est**. *Pandōra* ab Iove in coniugium Epimetheō **data est**. Fīlia eōrum **erat** *Pyrrha*, prīma mortālis.
It describes who Prometheus is
male, dative, singular. first conjugation active indicative
it describes and refers to Pandora, and is in the genitive case
linking, omnes refers to the gifts, Dei dona is the object, ei miserunt is the verb
1st conjugation, passive indicative. neuter, ablative, singular
ablative active
past tense
Long ago Prometheus, first son of Iapetus, fashioned men from mud. at the same time Vulcan created a woman from mud. Minerva gave this woman a soul and sent all of the Gods' gifts. hence the name "pandora" was given to her. Pandora was given in marriage by Jupiter to Epimetheus. Their daughter was Pyrrha, the first mortal
